<!-- SC_OFF --><div class="md"><p>Just a project I was working on because I wanted a temperature monitor I could call up by command whenever I want to check the system temperature.</p> <p>Check out the repo and feel free to share if you or anyone else want to use it.</p> <p><a href="https://github.com/kawilkins/TemperatureMonitor">https://github.com/kawilkins/TemperatureMonitor</a></p> <p>It essentially takes the data from the `/sys/class/thermal/thermal_zone0/temp` file and outputs it in human readable format (Celsius, Fahrenheit, and Kelvin). Simple and straight forward.</p> </div><!-- SC_ON --> &#32; submitted by &#32; <a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/kwilk1984"> /u/kwilk1984 </a> <br/> <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/linux/comments/w5uxwl/my_project_system_temperature_monitor/">[link]</a></span> &#32; <span><a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/linux/comments/w5uxwl/my_project_system_temperature_monitor/">[comments]</a></span>